You've arrived here looking for something, certainly not me, but I can help you in your search.
I propose you a game:

> Page2

You are a man.

> Page3

A man walking alone.

> Page4

Through the city.

> Page5

The city always turns orange in the sunset, and you walk the crowded streets.

> Page6

Make this walk every day.

> Page7

Walking the same trails. See the same lanterns.
Neon lights. The sun in the distance.
Trees. Buildings. Palms. The tram.
The planes, the people.
The amusement park, where you have never entered.
Someone greets you:

> Page8

Is Emma, the species seller.
Diego also, the doorman of the tower where you used to live.
You love this city. Feel that belongs to you somehow. Usually thought it has been built for yourself.

> Page9

In the distance you see the mountains. A river. You hear the waves.
You know this city almost as yourself.
Until now.

> Page10

On the floor in front of you lies a dying boy. Just fell from a balcony and is bleeding on the sidewalk. People gather on the scene. You see the blood. Then your vision turns black. Then everything revolves. Someone shouts from above but you faint.

> Page11

Now you are coming back. Your eyes take time to adjust to the new reality. Finally able to stand among a thick fog.

> Page12

It's cold. You’re freezing.
As a runaway roller coaster the tragic image come back to your mind. The dead child. But now there is nothing on the sidewalk. Nobody. All the block lies in solitude.
You walk.

> Page13

Nature seems dead. Not a soul round the streets.
Walks alone.

> Page14

The windows look old, like from another time. The rusty buildings, traffic lights no longer work.
Through your city.

> Page15

One of the most popular sources is dry. Even in the place where the girl and the young man were moments ago, now there are only a couple of broken mannequins on the gravel. What happened?

> Page16

Your voice sounds cold. Rumbles into nothingness. No one replied.
It starts to drizzle. The drizzle soon becomes overwhelming rain.

> Page17

You trying to cover, but something push you to keep walking. The air becomes oxide to your lungs.
You don´t know how you have reached here. Just remember that kid dying...

> Page18

Your mind hears screams but cannot identify from where they’re come. Memories of the accident, maybe... Cuttings.
Why did not anyone help me?
Someone peeks out from behind some trees.

> Page19

Hello? Anyone? Diego...? Emma...?
The noises go away.

> Page20

Ask for help but no one comes. Do you know that no one helps the homeless and the insane?

> Page21

You takes several minutes touring downtown but feels somehow stalling, spinning in the same circle.
You concludes that this city is another, very different from where you come. Here you are lost.

> Page22

Am I lost?
Worn irons, the trails full of leftover trash. All lights off.

> Page23

Slowly begins to dawn. With some clarity things look better.

> Page24

The sunrise, the river, the towers, the amusement park that never visited. Everything was real.

> Page25

The fog begins to dissipate.
In front of you a large marquee closes the view. It is the entrance to the old amusement park. But you don’t want to go in there.

> Page26

But you go in.

> Page27

The attractions are abandoned. Everything seems to merge with the state of the city.
A cold breeze hits your face. The wind brings familiars smells.
You walk.

> Page28

At every step you feel a huge force contracting your chest. Everything what you see feels so close...

> Page29

View the high pastures full of roasted peanuts bags and cigarette packs. Watch the knife carved benches. Someone with your name ever passed through here.
A sharp pain hits your temples:

> Page30

Now everything is covered by a deep rust, but I know this place or what once was. We used to get together here every Saturday under the palm trees... From here we could see almost all: people spinning in circles, planes, the tram, the mountains...
Hear the screams again but this time they feel more real and not too far away.

> Page31

Your body trembles. Begin to feel that you´re living into a dream.

> Page32

But the air cools my chest... The rain wets my shoes...
Another cry. It's a kid.

> Page33

Please...!
You freaking out. Walk faster. Still not understand how, but recognizes that voice.

> Page34

… FATHER!
You can't breathe.

> Page35

In front of you is "LA VUELTA AL MUNDO" and now-

> Page36

At this point it all starts to make sense. Not the sunrise which illuminates the scene, but something brighter. Something almost blinding. AND YOU REMEMBER ALL.

> Page37

Now the trails are not more trails.
The streetlights are no longer streetlights.
The river no longer flows. Citizens no longer collide.
The rain ceases.
You've arrived here looking for something, certainly not me, but I can help you in your search. I propose you a game: lolls your mind. Question your vision. Look through the veil:

> Page38

Now you see that kid falling down again. A hand that fails to hold the body in the highest. A face that looks heartbreakingly screaming...
Watch it.

> Page39

There’s no city. Never was. Just a fantasy prison.
Just painful memories, cuttings waiting to join.

> Page40

Your son Diego, your wife Emma, both falling...
People gather around. You perceive them but not see them because tears cover your eyes.
... and fading into your arms.
Call for help.

> Page41

Nobody helps the homeless, remember? Neither the insane.

> Page42

They begin to strike you until you fall unconscious.

> Page43

Now you are coming back. Your eyes take time to adjust to the light...
You spent several years living tied to your own way of forgetting, Leonard, to avoid trauma: your imagination. You have decided to remove that day, that place. The tragic loss of your family.
But trust me, I'm your friend and I'm waiting for you.

> Page44

Warm full earth. The sunrise is beautiful. Until now you have lived in a dream and it's time to go awakening. You have done well, but now you must return.

> Page45

I need you come back here, Leonard...

> Page46

It's time to wake up!

